## Answer

**Pi coding agent SDK for custom tools** — two registration paths, clear security model, pluggable operations for scope restriction.

---

## 1. How to Define Custom Tools

### via Extension (`pi.registerTool()`)

```typescript
import type { ExtensionAPI } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
import { Type } from "typebox";

export default function (pi: ExtensionAPI) {
  pi.registerTool({
    name: "greet",
    label: "Greeting",
    description: "Greet someone by name",
    promptSnippet: "Greet a person",
    promptGuidelines: ["Use greet when the user asks to be greeted"],
    parameters: Type.Object({
      name: Type.String({ description: "Name to greet" }),
    }),
    async execute(toolCallId, params, signal, onUpdate, ctx) {
      return {
        content: [{ type: "text", text: `Hello, ${params.name}!` }],
        details: {},
      };
    },
  });
}
```

### via SDK (`defineTool()` + `customTools`)

```typescript
import { defineTool, createAgentSession } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
import { Type } from "typebox";

const myTool = defineTool({
  name: "my_tool",
  label: "My Tool",
  description: "Does something useful",
  parameters: Type.Object({
    input: Type.String({ description: "Input value" }),
  }),
  execute: async (_toolCallId, params) => ({
    content: [{ type: "text", text: `Result: ${params.input}` }],
    details: {},
  }),
});

const { session } = await createAgentSession({
  customTools: [myTool],
  tools: ["read", "bash", "my_tool"],  // must include custom tool name
});
```

`defineTool()` preserves parameter type inference through arrays. Inline `pi.registerTool()` already infers correctly.

---

## 2. ToolDefinition Interface (Full Shape)

From `dist/core/extensions/types.d.ts`:

```typescript
export interface ToolDefinition<TParams extends TSchema, TDetails = unknown, TState = any> {
  name: string;
  label: string;
  description: string;
  promptSnippet?: string;                // One-line for "Available tools" in system prompt
  promptGuidelines?: string[];           // Bullets added to "Guidelines" section
  parameters: TParams;                   // TypeBox schema
  renderShell?: "default" | "self";      // Self-managed framing
  prepareArguments?: (args: unknown) => Static<TParams>; // Backward compat shim
  executionMode?: "sequential" | "parallel"; // Per-tool parallelism override
  execute(toolCallId: string, params: Static<TParams>, signal: AbortSignal | undefined,
          onUpdate: AgentToolUpdateCallback<TDetails> | undefined,
          ctx: ExtensionContext): Promise<AgentToolResult<TDetails>>;
  renderCall?: (args: Static<TParams>, theme: Theme, context: ToolRenderContext<TState, Static<TParams>>) => Component;
  renderResult?: (result: AgentToolResult<TDetails>, options: ToolRenderResultOptions,
                  theme: Theme, context: ToolRenderContext<TState, Static<TParams>>) => Component;
}
```

Key properties:
- **`name`** — used in system prompt tool definitions and LLM tool_call requests
- **`parameters`** — TypeBox schema; use `StringEnum` (from `@earendil-works/pi-ai`) instead of `Type.Union`/`Type.Literal` for Google API compatibility
- **`execute` return** — `{ content: TextContent[], details: TDetails, terminate?: boolean }`
- **`terminate: true`** — skips automatic follow-up LLM call (see `structured-output.ts` example)
- **Error signaling** — throw an Error to mark `isError: true`; returning never sets error flag
- **`promptSnippet`** — without it, custom tools are left out of the "Available tools" system prompt section

