## 4. Security Model & Restrictions

### Full system permissions for extensions
> **Security:** Extensions run with your full system permissions and can execute arbitrary code. Only install from sources you trust.

Extensions are TypeScript modules loaded via jiti. No sandbox by default.

### Tool call interception (gate pattern)
Extensions can block/modify ANY tool call via the `tool_call` event:

```typescript
pi.on("tool_call", async (event, ctx) => {
  if (event.toolName === "bash" && event.input.command?.includes("rm -rf")) {
    const ok = await ctx.ui.confirm("Dangerous!", "Allow rm -rf?");
    if (!ok) return { block: true, reason: "Blocked by user" };
  }
  // For write/edit tools
  if (event.toolName === "write" && event.input.path?.includes(".env")) {
    return { block: true, reason: "Protected path" };
  }
  return undefined; // Allow
});
```

### OS-level sandbox (sandbox example)
The `sandbox/` extension uses `@anthropic-ai/sandbox-runtime` to enforce filesystem and network restrictions at OS level (sandbox-exec on macOS, bubblewrap on Linux) via **overriding the bash tool's operations**:

```typescript
import { createBashTool, type BashOperations } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

const sandboxedOps: BashOperations = {
  async exec(command, cwd, { onData, signal, timeout }) {
    const wrappedCommand = await SandboxManager.wrapWithSandbox(command);
    // spawn with sandbox wrapper...
  },
};

pi.registerTool({
  ...localBash,  // spread the built-in bash tool definition
  name: "bash",
  async execute(id, params, signal, onUpdate) {
    const sandboxedBash = createBashTool(cwd, { operations: sandboxedOps });
    return sandboxedBash.execute(id, params, signal, onUpdate);
  },
});
```

